Covid Data Exploration

Madeleine Guettler

2023-04-19

Introduction

This time series exploration focuses on daily confirmed covid cases in Singapore collected by Hui Xiang Chua.For the exploration I focused on daily data from January 23, 2020 to January 23, 2022. Throughout this project I attempted to fit daily confirmed covid case ARIMA models, monthly average confirmed covide case ARIMA models, and finally a light exploration of Regime Switching Models.

Generally it looks like we see the initial spike when covid started and as restrictions increased Singapore went through a fairly stable period. In looking at Singapore guidelines around mid of 2021 restriction protocols started to ease which potentially could explain the spike in cases. There also seems to be a pattern of spikes in the mid point of 2020 and 2021.

Decomposition

covid_confirmed_ts.decom = decompose(covid_confirmed_ts) 
plot(covid_confirmed_ts.decom)

Top: Actual observed data would be the same as plot(co2) Second: Trend- overall direction of data Third: Seasonality- pattern. How much we’re going up and down from our trend Fourth: Measurement error, uncertainty

In previous plot we had noted that both 2021 and 2022 years had a similar trend in covid data after about half the year. This we see in our seasonal plot as we see basically identical plots at these time plots, and it would be interesting to tease apart more these specific time periods in the year.

ADF and ACF plot

adf.test(covid_confirmed_ts)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  covid_confirmed_ts
## Dickey-Fuller = -1.9171, Lag order = 9, p-value = 0.6134
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
acf(covid_confirmed_ts)

adf.test(covid_confirmed_ts)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  covid_confirmed_ts
## Dickey-Fuller = -1.9171, Lag order = 9, p-value = 0.6134
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

It does not seem like this model is stationary in anyway as we are far from seeing lags within the boundaries or any sign of exponential decay. Because of this we will try to make model stationary by differencing and also performing a log function as there appears to be variance in our data.

Differencing

covid_diff = diff(covid_confirmed_ts)
covid_diff365 = diff(covid_diff, 365)
covid_19 = covid_confirmed_ts + 0.00001
covid_diff = diff(log(covid_19))

Note We have added 0.00001 to each observation in our data to avoid accidentally creating NA values when perform the log function on data and also difference the data.

Acf/pacf plot

Let’s look at our ACF and PACF plots again to see if our plots are stationary now.

plot(covid_diff)

adf.test(covid_diff)
## Warning in adf.test(covid_diff): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  covid_diff
## Dickey-Fuller = -11.71, Lag order = 8, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
acf(covid_diff, lag.max = 365)

pacf(covid_diff, lag.max = 365)

acf(covid_diff, lag.max = 21)

pacf(covid_diff, lag.max = 21)

auto.arima(covid_diff)

With a p-value of 0.01 we can conclude that we can reject our null hypothesis and instead conclude our alternative hypothesis that the model is stationary. We see this as well in looking at our acf and pacf tests. In looking at the acf plot the model goes into exponential decay much quicker, where it looks like by lag 2 our model is pretty much consistently within our boundaries. In terms of the pacf plot it looks like by lag 7 it cuts off. From this we could conclude a possible model could be ARIMA(7,1,2). I will also do the ARIMA(5,1,2) model as that was predicted as best fitting by our auto.arima function.

Forecasting

The following function allows us to calculate a bias correct AIC value.

AIC.to.AICC <- function (aic, n, pq1) {
  aic - 2 * pq1 + 2 * n * pq1 / (n - 1 - pq1) } 
auto.arima(covid_confirmed_ts)
## Series: covid_confirmed_ts 
## ARIMA(5,1,4) 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1      ar2      ar3      ar4      ar5      ma1     ma2      ma3
##       0.1626  -0.9602  -0.1373  -0.4789  -0.5733  -0.7013  1.2458  -0.5555
## s.e.  0.0552   0.0383   0.0647   0.0299   0.0384   0.0682  0.0566   0.0619
##          ma4
##       0.7151
## s.e.  0.0332
## 
## sigma^2 = 36091:  log likelihood = -4862.87
## AIC=9745.74   AICc=9746.05   BIC=9791.67
m3 = arima(covid_confirmed_ts, order = c(7,1,2), include.mean = F)
m4 = arima(covid_confirmed_ts, order = c(5,1,4), include.mean = F)

m3$aic
## [1] 9784.836
m4$aic
## [1] 9745.744
AIC.to.AICC(m3$aic, 730, 10)
## [1] 9785.142
AIC.to.AICC(m4$aic, 730, 10)
## [1] 9746.05

In the case of these two models generated using the original undifferenced and logged data, the best performing model seems to be the model suggested by auto.arima().

Further exploration into how well model fits

Now that we have our models let’s see how well the model fits by looking at how normal our distributions are. We will look at several tests. First we will look at the histograms of both our ARIMA models.

hist(m3$residuals)

hist(m4$residuals)

The models created with the original data set, look a little better normally distributed. The two models are still not amazingly normally distributed but certainly less skewed.

Plots of residuals

Let’s look at our ACF and PACF models for the residuals.

acf(m3$residuals, lag.max = 100)

pacf(m3$residuals, lag.max = 100)

acf(m4$residuals, lag.max = 100)

pacf(m4$residuals, lag.max = 100)

Both models have issues of spikes that do not allow us to conclude that we have white noise in our models.

#Shapiro-Wilk Normality Test Another test we can do is the Shapiro-Wilk Normality Test. If we have a p-value less than 0.05 we are able to reject our null hypothesis that our models are normally distributed and instead conclude the alternative hypothesis that not normally distributed.

shapiro.test(m3$residuals)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  m3$residuals
## W = 0.5916, p-value < 2.2e-16
shapiro.test(m4$residuals)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  m4$residuals
## W = 0.60356, p-value < 2.2e-16

With both models at 5% significance level having shapiro wilk p-values less then 0.05, we are able to reject our null hypothesis and instead conclude that the data doesn’t come a normally distributed population.

#Ljung-Box Test The Ljung-Box test also allows us to assess lack of fit. Where our null hypothesis is that there is no lack of fit while our alternative hypothesis is that there is a lack of fit.

Box.test(m3$residuals, lag = 30, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  m3$residuals
## X-squared = 162.16, df = 30, p-value < 2.2e-16
Box.test(m4$residuals, lag = 30, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  m4$residuals
## X-squared = 124.12, df = 30, p-value = 2.065e-13

With p-values still less than 0.05, at the 5% significance level, we are able to conclude that there is a lack of fit.

#qqnorm plots The last test we can perform are qqnorm plots where we want out points and line to be as in line as possible.

qqnorm(m3$residuals)
qqline(m3$residuals)

qqnorm(m4$residuals)
qqline(m4$residuals)

It appears that all four of our models, also fail our qqplot test, where none fit particularly well to our line of reference.

Overall, given that all four models seem to have failed all of our checks to see if a good model, none of these models seem to be correctly fitted to our data.

Averaged Data

Now let’s look at how successful we are with creating models if we explore averaged monthly confirmed covid cases.

library(readxl)
Covid19_avg <- read_excel("Covid19_avg.xlsx")

covid_avg_ts <- ts(Covid19_avg[,4], start = c(2020, 1), end = c(2022, 1), frequency = 12)
plot(covid_avg_ts)

boxplot(covid_avg_ts ~ cycle(covid_avg_ts))

plot(decompose(covid_avg_ts))

adf.test(covid_avg_ts)
## Warning in adf.test(covid_avg_ts): p-value greater than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  covid_avg_ts
## Dickey-Fuller = -0.027872, Lag order = 2, p-value = 0.99
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
acf(covid_avg_ts, lag.max = 24)

pacf(covid_avg_ts, lag.max = 24)

auto.arima(covid_avg_ts)
## Series: covid_avg_ts 
## ARIMA(0,1,0) 
## 
## sigma^2 = 561986:  log likelihood = -192.93
## AIC=387.85   AICc=388.03   BIC=389.03

Our data looks stationary here where we have in our acf plot a cut off at lag 1 and in our pacf plot we have a cut off as well at lag 1. From these cut offs we could conclude a ARIMA(1,0,1) model. Additionally our auto.arima function suggests an ARIMA(0,1,0) model so we will try this as well.

Fitting ARIMA model

avg1 = arima(covid_avg_ts, order = c(1,0,1), include.mean = F)
avg2 = arima(covid_avg_ts, order = c(0,1,0), include.mean = F)

#Compare models 
avg1$aic
## [1] 398.0127
avg2$aic
## [1] 387.8506
AIC.to.AICC(avg1$aic, 25,3)
## [1] 399.1556
AIC.to.AICC(avg2$aic, 25,2)
## [1] 388.3961

A way to see which model is the better fitting model we can compare our model’s Akaike Information criteria (AIC) and bias corrected AIC values to see which model was better. Because our second model has the lower AIC and AICC values the ARIMA(0,1,0) seems to be the better fitting model.

Residual examination

Let’s still look at how our residual distributions look.

hist(avg1$residuals)

hist(avg2$residuals)

Our ARIMA(1,0,1) model looks right skewed here so not quite normally distributed. Similarly our model that was suggested by auto.arima also does not look normally distributed.

#Shaprio-Wilks Test

shapiro.test(avg1$residuals)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  avg1$residuals
## W = 0.69166, p-value = 5.64e-06
shapiro.test(avg2$residuals)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  avg2$residuals
## W = 0.74197, p-value = 2.826e-05

At the 5% significance level with a p-value of 5.64e-06 > 0.05 we are able to reject our null hypothesis and conclude our alternative that our ARIMA(1,0,1) model does not come from a normally distributed populations. Similarly our ARIMA(0,1,0) model also with a p-value of 2.826e-05 does not come from a normally distributed population.

Ljung-Box Test

Box.test(avg1$residuals, lag = 20, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  avg1$residuals
## X-squared = 10.401, df = 20, p-value = 0.9603
Box.test(avg2$residuals, lag = 20, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  avg2$residuals
## X-squared = 12.824, df = 20, p-value = 0.8848

At the 5% significance level, with a p-value of 0.9603 for our ARIMA(1,0,1) model, we are unable to reject our null hypothesis that the data is independently distributed. Similarly with a p-value of 0.8848 for our ARIMA(0,1,0) model, we are unable to reject our null hypothesis that the data is independently distributed.

qqnorm(avg1$residuals)
qqline(avg1$residuals)

qqnorm(avg2$residuals)
qqline(avg2$residuals)

acf(avg1$residuals)

pacf(avg1$residuals)

plot(avg1$residuals)

acf(avg2$residuals)

pacf(avg2$residuals)

plot(avg2$residuals)

Again, both models failed the qqplot test and neither were normally distributed.

Hamilton Regime Switching Model

Because our typical way of fitting arima models didn’t result in terribly well fitting models I wanted to explore how a regime switching Model performed. What I found was that when I employed a two state regime, I ended with a better AIC score of 312.906 for this model then the average best performing ARIMA(0,1,0) model with an AIC score of 388.396.

inf <- Covid19_avg[,4]
ninf <- nrow(inf)

ninf

y1 <- inf[1:(ninf-1),]

#Two State
